validity_information_studypaper:
content validity: pilot study; N = 10; 
convergent validity: corrected total item correlation (table 18) and 
discriminant validity: inter-correlations (table 18): computer security practices; perceived vulnerability; perceived severity; response efficacy;  perceived usefulness; perceived ease of use; awareness; attitude toward computer security practices; subjective norms; perceived behavioral control

content validity: Field testing of the instrument prior to its use in the present study was not required due to the instrument’s established validity;
convergent validity: AVE >0.5 and
discriminant validity: Fornell-Lacker: attitude; information security awareness; intention to comply; normative beliefs;
reference to results of original scale development by Bulgurcu et al. (2010): convergent validity (loadings >0.7; AVE >0.5) and factor validity (CFA, unidimensional constructs)

intervention_description:
differentiation of control group and treatment group; 
The control group was then exposed to four general government-related news stories. 
The treatment group was exposed to four news stories related specifically to government surveillance programs.

8 week cyber academy teaching cybersecurity skills and career awareness (3-5 hours online course daily);  pre- and post measure of self-efficacy
modules targeted to develop content knowledge in computational thinking, computer programming, and cybersecurity knowledge, skills, and abilities; Increase awareness of cybersecurity and CS educational and vocational pathways; Increase interest in taking CS and cybersecurity courses at school; 
course modules: introduction to cybersecurity & cybercrime; cryptography & industry awareness; networking & server attacks; wireless network security; authentication, account and access management; vulnerability assessment and ehtical hacking; secure system design; database principles;  additional discussions with 16 speakers from industry and government; 
weekly workshop tasks/competitive activities: simulation of the installation of malicious software & incident reporting (Cadets receive a phishing email, supposedly signed by the instructor, indicating the need to view a webpage for updated exercise information that contains a simulated virus string); simulation of a network denial service attack (An increased amount of network traffic is generated on the network that results in reduced performance for users); developping a product analysis report (Cadets made product selection recommendations in light of known threats and vulnerabilities, using CVEdetails.com, a free security vulnerability website. Each team analyzes vulnerabilities of three products and present their findings and recommendations);  developping an internet of things challenge using tinkercard (As an Arduino team project, cadets create a stoplight/intersection system); developping a security plan for a physical location (Teams develop a plan for the physical security of a student-run data center.)
